Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a point in the $xz$-plane, so $\mathbf{P}=(x,0,z).$ By theDistance Formula, we have \begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{P}-\begin{pmatrix}1\\-1\\0\end{pmatrix}\|&=\|\mathbf{P}-\begin{pmatrix}2\\1\\2\end{pmatrix}\|,\\\sqrt{(x-1)^2+(-1-0)^2+(0-0)^2}&=\sqrt{(x-2)^2+(0-1)^2+(z-2)^2},\\(x-1)^2+1&=(x-2)^2+(z-2)^2,\\x^2-2x+1+1&=x^2-4x+4+z^2-4z+4,\\2x+2z&=6+z^2,\end{align*}and \begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{P}-\begin{pmatrix}1\\-1\\0\end{pmatrix}\|&=\|\mathbf{P}-\begin{pmatrix}3\\2\\-1\end{pmatrix}\|,\\\sqrt{(x-1)^2+(-1-0)^2+(0-0)^2}&=\sqrt{(x-3)^2+(2-0)^2+(z+1)^2},\\(x-1)^2+1&=(x-3)^2+(2)^2+(z+1)^2,\\x^2-2x+1+1&=x^2-6x+9+4+z^2+2z+1,\\4x-2z&=12+z^2.\end{align*}Subtracting the previous equation and the new one, we have $6x-4z=-6,$ or $3x-2z=-3.$ Let $z=3t,$ so $3x-6t=-3,$ or $x=2t-1.$ Then \[\mathbf{P}=\begin{pmatrix}x\\0\\z\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}2t-1\\0\\3t\end{pmatrix}.\]In particular, when $t=1,$ we have $\mathbf{P}=\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}1\\0\\3\end{pmatrix}},$ which is our desired point. $\blacksquare$</think> <answer>The point is $(1,0,3).$
